=========================================================
Rule of 5 - Interview Ready Example
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
#include <algorithm>
using namespace std;

class Buffer
{
private:
    int* data;
    int size;

public:

    // 1. Constructor
    Buffer(int n)
        : size(n)
    {
        data = new int[size];
        cout << "Constructor\n";
    }

    // 2. Destructor
    ~Buffer()
    {
        delete[] data;
        cout << "Destructor\n";
    }

    // 3. Copy Constructor
    Buffer(const Buffer& other)
        : size(other.size)
    {
        data = new int[size];

        for (int i = 0; i < size; i++)
            data[i] = other.data[i];

        cout << "Copy Constructor\n";
    }

    // 4. Copy Assignment Operator
    Buffer& operator=(const Buffer& other)
    {
        cout << "Copy Assignment\n";

        if (this == &other)
            return *this;

        int* temp = new int[other.size];***** use temp not ptr here directly 

        for (int i = 0; i < other.size; i++)
            temp[i] = other.data[i];

        delete[] data;

        data = temp;
        size = other.size;

        return *this;
    }

    // 5. Move Constructor
    Buffer(Buffer&& other) noexcept
        : data(other.data),
          size(other.size)
    {
        other.data = nullptr;
        other.size = 0;

        cout << "Move Constructor\n";
    }

    // 6. Move Assignment Operator
    Buffer& operator=(Buffer&& other) noexcept
    {
        cout << "Move Assignment\n";

        if (this == &other)
            return *this;

        delete[] data;

        data = other.data;
        size = other.size;

        other.data = nullptr;
        other.size = 0;

        return *this;
    }
};

=========================================================
Rule of 5
=========================================================

If a class manages a resource (heap memory, file handle,
socket, mutex, etc.) and defines any one of these:

1. Destructor
2. Copy Constructor
3. Copy Assignment Operator
4. Move Constructor
5. Move Assignment Operator

then it usually needs to define all five.

=========================================================
Why Rule of 5 for Buffer?
=========================================================

Buffer owns:

    int* data

Compiler-generated copy operations perform SHALLOW COPY:

b1.data ----+
            |
b2.data ----+

Both objects point to the same memory.

When destructors run:

delete[] data;
delete[] data;

=> Double delete (Undefined Behavior)

Therefore, we must implement:

✓ Deep copy operations
✓ Move operations
✓ Destructor

=========================================================
Interview One-Liner
=========================================================

Rule of 5 states that if a class manages a resource and
defines any one of destructor, copy constructor, copy
assignment, move constructor, or move assignment, it
should usually define all five to correctly manage
ownership and avoid resource leaks, double deletion,
and expensive copies.
